sle of Man</li>\n</ul>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice help-notice\">\n<p>If you’re single, you can’t apply for a parental order.</p>\n</div>\n\n<h2>How to apply</h2>\n\n<p>You must fill in a <a rel=\"external\" href=\"http://hmctsformfinder.justice.gov.uk/HMCTS/GetForm.do?court_forms_id=2397\" title=\"C51 application form for a parental order\">‘C51 application form for a parental order’</a> and give this to a <a rel=\"external\" href=\"http://hmctscourtfinder.justice.gov.uk/HMCTS/\" title=\"Find your local family proceedings court\">family proceedings court</a> within 6 months of the child’s birth.</p>\n\n<p>You&rsquo;ll need to provide the child&rsquo;s full birth certificate and will also be charged a court fee of £200.</p>\n\n<p>The court will then set a date for the hearing and issue you with a &lsquo;C52 acknowledgement form&rsquo; that you must give to the child&rsquo;s legal parent, ie your surrogate.</p>\n\n<p>The birth mother and anyone else who&rsquo;s a parent of the child must agree to the parental order <a rel=\"external\" href=\"http://hmctsformfinder.justice.gov.uk/HMCTS/GetForm.do?court_forms_id=2396\" title=\"Form A101A: Agreement to the making of a parental order in respect of my child\">in writing.</a></p>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice info-notice\">\n<p>You can’t apply for a parental order once the child is older than 6 months.</p>\n</div>\n\n<h2>Adoption</h2>\n\n<p>If neither you or your partner are related to the child, or you’re single, <a href=\"/child-adoption/overview\" title=\"Child adoption\">adoption</a> is the only way you can become the child&rsquo;s legal parent.</p>\n\n<p>If you choose to adopt, a <a rel=\"external\" href=\"http://www.cvaa.org.uk/adopters/vaasearch.php\" title=\"Contact a voluntary adoption agency\">registered adoption agency</a> must be involved in your surrogacy process.</p>\n","alternative_title":""},"tags":[{"title":"Having a child, parenting and adoption","id":"https://www.gov.uk/api/tags/births-deaths-marriages%2Fchild-adoption.json","web_url":null,"details":{"description":"Legal rights, birth certificates, parental rights and child maintenance","short_description":"","type":"section"},"content_with_tag":{"id":"https://www.gov.uk/api/with_tag.json?tag=births-deaths-marriages%2Fchild-adoption","web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/browse/births-deaths-marriages/child-adoption"},"parent":{"title":"Births, deaths, marriages and care","id":"https://www.gov.uk/api/tags/births-deaths-marriages.json","web_url":null,"details":{"description":"Includes civil partnerships, splitting up and Lasting Power of Attorney","short_description":"","type":"section"},"content_with_tag":{"id":"https://www.gov.uk/api/with_tag.json?tag=births-deaths-marriages","web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/browse/births-deaths-marriages"},"parent":null}}],"related":[{"id":"https://www.gov.uk/api/child-adoption.json","web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/child-adoption","title":"Child adoption","format":"guide","updated_at":"2012-11-01T12:35:58+00:00"},{"id":"https://www.gov.uk/api/legal-rights-when-using-surrogates-and-donors.json","web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/legal-rights-when-using-surrogates-and-donors","title":"Legal rights when using surrogates and donors","format":"guide","updated_at":"2012-11-09T13:37:03+00:00"}]},{"id":"https://www.gov.uk/api/child-trust-funds.json","web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/child-trust-funds","title":"Child Trust Fund","format":"guide","updated_at":"2012-12-04T14:52:31+00:00","details":{"need_id":"868","business_proposition":false,"description":"Child Trust Fund is a long-term tax-free savings account for children - opening an account, providers, payments, managing the account","language":"en","alternative_title":"","video_summary":"","video_url":"","parts":[{"web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/child-trust-funds/overview","slug":"overview","order":1,"title":"Overview","body":"<p>A Child Trust Fund (<abbr title=\"Child Trust Fund\">CTF</abbr>) is a long-term tax-free savings account for children.</p>\n\n<h2>Who can get a <abbr title=\"Child Trust Fund\">CTF</abbr> account</h2>\n\n<p>Your child is entitled if all the following apply:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>they were born between 1 September 2002 and 2 January 2011</li>\n  <li>you were paid <a href=\"/child-benefit\" title=\"Child Benefit\">Child Benefit</a> for them for at least one day before 4 January 2011</li>\n  <li>your child lives in the UK</li>\n  <li>they are not subject to any immigration restriction </li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>If your child is looked after by a local council</h3>\n\n<p>They can still get a <abbr title=\"Child Trust Fund\">CTF</abbr> account if both the following apply:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>they were looked after by a local council before 3 April 2011</li>\n  <li>they meet the other qualifying conditions above (excluding child benefit)</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>If you work overseas and get a European family benefit</h3>\n\n<p>Your child can still get a <abbr title=\"Child Trust Fund\">CTF</abbr> account if all of the following apply:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>they were born between 1 September 2002 and 2 January 2011</li>\n  <li>your child lives in the UK</li>\n  <li>you were paid a family benefit by another European Union country for at least one day before 4 January 2011</li>\n  <li>you work in that same country</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h2>How it works</h2>\n\n<p>HM Revenue &amp; Customs (<abbr title=\"HM Revenue &amp; Customs\">HMRC</abbr>) sends you a voucher for each child that&rsquo;s entitled to a <abbr title=\"Child Trust Fund\">CTF</abbr> account. You use this to open the account in your child&rsquo;s name.</p>\n\n<p>You can add up to £3,600 a year to the account. The money belongs to the child but can&rsquo;t be taken out until they are 18.</p>\n\n<p>You could get extra money paid directly into the account - if you&rsquo;re on a low income, for example.</p>\n\n<p>There&rsquo;s no tax to pay on the <abbr title=\"Child Trust Fund\">CTF</abbr> income or any profits it makes. It won&rsquo;t affect any benefits or tax credits you receive.</p>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice info-notice\">\n<p>If your child isn’t eligible for a <abbr title=\"Child Trust Fund\">CTF</abbr> account, you may be able to open a <a href=\"/junior-individual-savings-accounts/overview\" title=\"Junior Individual Savings Accounts (ISA)\">Junior ISA</a> instead.</p>\n</div>\n\n"},{"web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/child-trust-funds/child-trust-fund-vouchers","slug":"child-trust-fund-vouchers","order":2,"title":"Child Trust Fund vouchers","body":"<p>The voucher could be worth £250 or £50 depending on when your child became entitled to an account.</p>\n\n<p>£250 is paid if:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>you first got Child Benefit (or a European family benefit) for your child on or before 2 August 2010</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>£50 is paid if:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>you first got Child Benefit (or a European family benefit) for your child on or after 3 August 2010 but before 4 January 2011</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h2>Who gets the voucher</h2>\n\n<p>The voucher is sent to the person who gets Child Benefit (or the European family benefit).</p>\n\n<p>If a local council started to look after your child before you claimed Child Benefit, HM Revenue &amp; Customs (<abbr title=\"HM Revenue &amp; Customs\">HMRC</abbr>) will open the account for them instead. </p>\n\n<h2>When to expect the voucher</h2>\n\n<p>You&rsquo;ll get the voucher within 4 weeks of getting Child Benefit.</p>\n\n<p>If you get a European family benefit, it may take slightly longer to arrive because <abbr title=\"HM Revenue &amp; Customs\">HMRC</abbr> needs to check that your child qualifies for a Child Trust Fund.</p>\n\n<h2>If you haven&rsquo;t got your voucher</h2>\n\n<p>You can get a replacement if:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>your voucher didn&rsquo;t arrive</li>\n  <li>you lost it</li>\n  <li>it was stolen</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>You can apply online for a replacement using different forms if:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li><a rel=\"external\" href=\"https://online.hmrc.gov.uk/shortforms/form/CTF_Replacement_Voucher_CB_Recipient?dept-name=CTF&amp;sub-dept-name=&amp;location=6&amp;origin=http://www.hmrc.gov.uk\" title=\"you're the person getting Child Benefit\">you&rsquo;re the person getting Child Benefit</a> </li>\n  <li>or if <a rel=\"external\" href=\"https://online.hmrc.gov.uk/shortforms/form/CTF_Replacement_Voucher_PR_Person?dept-name=CTF&amp;sub-dept-name=&amp;location=6&amp;origin=http://www.hmrc.gov.uk\" title=\"you have parental responsibility\">you have parental responsibility</a> but aren&rsquo;t the person getting Child Benefit </li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>If you don&rsquo;t get a replacement within a month, contact the <abbr title=\"Child Trust Fund\">CTF</abbr> Helpline:</p>\n\n<div class=\"contact\">\n<p><strong><abbr title=\"Child Trust Fund\">CTF</abbr> Helpline</strong>  </p>\n\n<p><strong>Telephone:</strong> 0845 302 1470<br />\n<strong>Textphone:</strong> 0845 366 7870<br />\n<strong>From outside the UK:</strong> +44 1355 359 002</p>\n</div>\n\n<h2>When you get your voucher</h2>\n\n<p>Check that your child&rsquo;s name and date of birth are correct - if not, contact the <abbr title=\"Child Trust Fund\">CTF</abbr> Helpline. The voucher has an expiry date, which is 60 days after it&rsquo;s issued.</p>\n\n<p>If you don&rsquo;t open an account by the expiry date, <abbr title=\"HM Revenue &amp; Customs\">HMRC</abbr> will open an account in your child&rsquo;s name. You&rsquo;ll be responsible for managing it.</p>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice info-notice\">\n<p><abbr title=\"HM Revenue &amp; Customs\">HMRC</abbr> will not be issuing any new vouchers after 31 October 2012 and will stop issuing replacement vouchers in December 2012.</p>\n</div>\n\n"},{"web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/child-trust-funds/extra-payments-","slug":"extra-payments-","order":3,"title":"Extra payments ","body":"<p>Your child could get extra payments in some circumstances.</p>\n\n<h2>If you&rsquo;re on a low income</h2>\n\n<p>Your child could get an extra payment of £250 or £50 on top of the starting payment. The amount you get will be the same as on your Child Trust Fund (<abbr title=\"Child Trust Fund\">CTF</abbr>) voucher.</p>\n\n<p>To get one of these payments both of the following must apply:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>you qualify for <a href=\"/child-tax-credit\" title=\"Child Tax Credit\">Child Tax Credit</a></li>\n  <li>you are on a &lsquo;low income&rsquo;</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>&lsquo;Low income&rsquo; means your total household income before tax was:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>£16,190 or less between 6 April 2010 and 5 April 2011</li>\n  <li>£16,040 or less between 6 April 2009 and 5 April 2010</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>HM Revenue &amp; Customs (<abbr title=\"HM Revenue &amp; Customs\">HMRC</abbr>) will pay these extra payments directly into your child&rsquo;s account after you have:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>renewed your <a href=\"/renewing-your-tax-credits-claim\" title=\"tax credits\">tax credits</a> (usually between April and July)</li>\n  <li>been sent your final tax credits award notice</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Your child could also qualify for the extra <abbr title=\"Child Trust Fund\">CTF</abbr> payment if you get any of the following for your child:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li><a href=\"/income-support\" title=\"Income Support\">Income Support</a></li>\n  <li>income-based <a href=\"/jobseekers-allowance\" title=\"Jobseeker's Allowance\">Jobseeker&rsquo;s Allowance</a></li>\n  <li><a href=\"/pension-credit\" title=\"Pension Credit\">Pension Credit</a></li>\n  <li><a href=\"/employment-support-allowance\" title=\"Employment and Support Allowance\">Employment and Support Allowance</a></li>\n</ul>\n\n<h2>If a local council looks after your child</h2>\n\n<p>If the local council started looking after your child before Child Benefit was claimed, the normal starting payment is doubled:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>£500 - paid if your child was born between 1 September 2002 and 1 August 2010</li>\n  <li>£100 - paid if your child was born between 2 August 2010 and 2 January 2011</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>If the local council started to look after your child after Child Benefit was claimed, your child won&rsquo;t be entitled to any extra money. They will just get the normal starting payment.</p>\n\n<h2>Backdated claims</h2>\n\n<p>Children who turned 7 between 1 September 2009 and 31 July 2010 or qualified for <a href=\"/dla-disability-living-allowance-benefit\" title=\"Disability Living Allowance\">Disability Living Allowance (DLA)</a> between 6 April 2009 and 5 April 2011 may be able to claim backdated payments.</p>\n\n<h2>Who to contact for help</h2>\n\n<p>If you think your child is entitled to extra <abbr title=\"Child Trust Fund\">CTF</abbr> payments but you haven&rsquo;t had them, contact the <abbr title=\"Child Trust Fund\">CTF</abbr> Helpline:</p>\n\n<div class=\"contact\">\n<p><strong><abbr title=\"Child Trust Fund\">CTF</abbr> Helpline</strong>  </p>\n\n<p><strong>Telephone:</strong> 0845 302 1470<br />\n<strong>Textphone:</strong> 0845 366 7870<br />\n<strong>From outside the UK:</strong> +44 1355 359 002</p>\n</div>\n\n"},{"web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/child-trust-funds/opening-an-account","slug":"opening-an-account","order":4,"title":"Opening an account","body":"<p>When you get your voucher, take it to an approved Child Trust Fund (<abbr title=\"Child Trust Fund\">CTF</abbr>) provider and they&rsquo;ll open the account for you. There are 3 main types of account. </p>\n\n<h2>Stakeholder accounts</h2>\n\n<p>These have to follow government rules, including:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>investing the money in a number of companies, not just one</li>\n  <li>moving the money to lower-risk investments when your child is 13</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>This helps protect your child&rsquo;s money. All <abbr title=\"Child Trust Fund\">CTF</abbr> providers offer stakeholder accounts.</p>\n\n<h2>Share accounts</h2>\n\n<p>These invest your child&rsquo;s money by buying shares in companies. The value can go up or down.</p>\n\n<h2>Savings accounts</h2>\n\n<p>These work in the same way 