 in the UK</li>\n  <li>working on secondment for a &lsquo;prescribed body&rsquo;, like a regional health authority or local authority</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p><a rel=\"external\" href=\"https://www2.dwp.gov.uk/csa/v2/en/contact/index.asp\" title=\"contact the CSA\">Contact the <abbr title=\"Child Support Agency\">CSA</abbr></a> for more information on how it can help.</p>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice info-notice\">\n<p>If you live in the UK and the paying parent lives in Australia, the <a href=\"http://www.csa.gov.au/\" title=\"Australian CSA\" rel=\"external\">Australian <abbr title=\"Child Support Agency\">CSA</abbr></a> might be able to help.</p>\n</div>\n\n<h2>If one of you lives in the European Union (<abbr title=\"European Union\">EU</abbr>)</h2>\n\n<p>By law, <a rel=\"external\" href=\"http://europa.eu/about-eu/countries/index_en.htm\" title=\"list of EU countries\"><abbr title=\"European Union\">EU</abbr> countries</a> must enforce:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>court orders for child maintenance</li>\n  <li>decisions made by the <abbr title=\"Child Support Agency\">CSA</abbr></li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Any of the following must apply:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>one of you lives in the <abbr title=\"European Union\">EU</abbr> and the other lives in the UK</li>\n  <li>the paying parent has valuable assets located in the <abbr title=\"European Union\">EU</abbr> - eg property, cars or money</li>\n</ul>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice info-notice\">\n<p><abbr title=\"European Union\">EU</abbr> countries can also make paying parents pay <abbr title=\"Child Support Agency\">CSA</abbr> debts if the money owed was from when both parents lived in the UK.</p>\n</div>\n\n<h2>If the paying parent lives outside of Australia and the <abbr title=\"European Union\">EU</abbr></h2>\n\n<p>If you have a court order for child maintenance you can try to get this enforced in a foreign country. You can also ask foreign authorities to create a court order for you. </p>\n\n<p>To do this, contact your local magistrates&rsquo; court (sheriff court in Scotland) using the links below: </p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li><a rel=\"external\" href=\"http://hmctscourtfinder.justice.gov.uk/HMCTS/\" title=\"find a court - England and Wales\">Find a court - England and Wales</a></li>\n  <li><a rel=\"external\" href=\"http://www.scotcourts.gov.uk/\" title=\"find a court - Scotland\">Find a court - Scotland</a></li>\n</ul>\n\n"},{"web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/child-maintenance-if-one-parent-lives-abroad/reciprocal-enforcement-of-maintenance-orders-remos","slug":"reciprocal-enforcement-of-maintenance-orders-remos","order":2,"title":"Reciprocal Enforcement of Maintenance Orders (REMOs)","body":"<p>These are international agreements about recognising and enforcing child maintenance orders. The UK has them with over 100 countries. </p>\n\n<p>If an agreement is in place, it means that:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>child maintenance orders made by UK courts can be registered and enforced in other countries</li>\n  <li>child maintenance orders made in foreign countries can be registered and enforced by UK courts</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>If you want to try and get an order enforced, you need to do one of the following things:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>contact the court where the order was made if you already have a court order for child maintenance</li>\n  <li>contact your local magistrates&rsquo; court (sheriff court in Scotland) if you haven’t got a court order</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>What happens next depends on where you live.</p>\n\n<h3>If you live in England or Wales</h3>\n\n<p>The court will send your case to the <abbr title=\"Reciprocal Enforcement of Maintenance Order\">REMO</abbr> unit, which deals with the foreign court on your behalf. You don’t need a solicitor.</p>\n\n<p>You can find out more about <abbr title=\"Reciprocal Enforcement of Maintenance Orders\">REMOs</abbr> on the <a rel=\"external\" href=\"http://www.justice.gov.uk/guidance/protecting-the-vulnerable/official-solicitor/\" title=\"Official Solicitor website\">Official Solicitor website.</a> </p>\n\n<h3>If you live in Scotland</h3>\n\n<p>If a court order already exists, the court that made it will send your case to the Justice Directorate.</p>\n\n<p>If a court order doesn’t exist, you can get one by either:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>applying to your local sheriff court</li>\n  <li>applying directly to the court in the country the other parent has moved to</li>\n</ul>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice info-notice\">\n<p>You’ll need to use a solicitor. Some of the <abbr title=\"Reciprocal Enforcement of Maintenance Order\">REMO</abbr> arrangements other countries have with the UK don’t apply to Scotland.</p>\n</div>\n\n<p>If you live in Scotland you can find out more about <abbr title=\"Reciprocal Enforcement of Maintenance Orders\">REMOs</abbr> on the <a rel=\"external\" href=\"http://www.scotland.gov.uk/Topics/Justice/law/17867/fm-children-root/maintenance\" title=\"Scottish Government website\">Scottish government website.</a></p>\n\n"}]},"tags":[{"title":"Having a child, parenting and adoption","id":"https://www.gov.uk/api/tags/births-deaths-marriages%2Fchild-adoption.json","web_url":null,"details":{"description":"Legal rights, birth certificates, parental rights and child maintenance","short_description":"","type":"section"},"content_with_tag":{"id":"https://www.gov.uk/api/with_tag.json?tag=births-deaths-marriages%2Fchild-adoption","web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/browse/births-deaths-marriages/child-adoption"},"parent":{"title":"Births, deaths, marriages and care","id":"https://www.gov.uk/api/tags/births-deaths-marriages.json","web_url":null,"details":{"description":"Includes civil partnerships, splitting up and Lasting Power of Attorney","short_description":"","type":"section"},"content_with_tag":{"id":"https://www.gov.uk/api/with_tag.json?tag=births-deaths-marriages","web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/browse/births-deaths-marriages"},"parent":null}},{"title":"Marriage, civil partnership and divorce","id":"https://www.gov.uk/api/t