 certificate (after a certain date, depending on which part of the UK the child was born in)</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>You can <a href=\"/parental-rights-responsibilities/apply-for-parental-responsibility\" title=\"Apply for parental responsibility\">apply for parental responsibility</a> if you don&rsquo;t automatically have it.</p>\n\n<h2>Births registered in England and Wales</h2>\n\n<p>If the parents of a child are married when the child is born, or if they&rsquo;ve jointly adopted a child, both have parental responsibility.</p>\n\n<p>They both keep parental responsibility if they later divorce.</p>\n\n<h3>Unmarried parents</h3>\n\n<p>An unmarried father can only get legal responsibility for his child in 1 of 3 ways:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>jointly registering the birth of the child with the mother (from 1 December 2003)</li>\n  <li>getting a parental responsibility agreement with the mother</li>\n  <li>getting a parental responsibility order from a court</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h2>Births registered in Scotland</h2>\n\n<p>A father has parental responsibility if he is married to the mother when the child is conceived, or marries her at any point afterwards. </p>\n\n<p>An unmarried father has parental responsibility if he is named on the child&rsquo;s birth certificate (from 4 May 2006).</p>\n\n<h2>Births registered in Northern Ireland</h2>\n<p>A father has parental responsibility if he is married to the mother at the time of the child&rsquo;s birth. </p>\n\n<p>If a father marries the mother after the child&rsquo;s birth, he has parental responsibility if he lives in Northern Ireland at the time of the marriage. </p>\n\n<p>An unmarried father has parental responsibility if he is named, or becomes named, on the child&rsquo;s birth certificate (from 15 April 2002).</p>\n\n<h2>Births registered outside the UK</h2>\n<p>If a child is born overseas and comes to live in the UK, who has parental responsibility depends on the UK country they&rsquo;re now living in.</p>\n"},{"web_url":"https://w