ted.</p>\n\n<p>Surrogacy contracts aren’t enforced by UK law, even if a contract has been signed with the intended parents and they&rsquo;ve paid for any expenses.</p>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice info-notice\">\n<p>It’s illegal to pay a surrogate in the UK, except for their reasonable expenses.</p>\n</div>\n\n<h2>Father’s rights</h2>\n\n<p>The child’s legal father or &lsquo;second parent&rsquo; is the surrogate’s husband or civil partner unless:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>legal rights are given to someone else through a <a href=\"/become-a-childs-legal-parent\" title=\"Become a child's legal parent\">parental order</a> or <a href=\"/child-adoption/overview\" title=\"Child adoption\">adoption</a></li>\n  <li>the surrogate’s husband or civil partner didn’t give their permission to their wife or partner</li>\n</ul>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice info-notice\">\n<p>If a surrogate has no partner, or they’re unmarried and not in a civil partnership, the child will have no legal father or second parent unless the partner actively consents.</p>\n</div>\n\n<h2>Maternity leave</h2>\n\n<p>Every pregnant employee has the right to 52 weeks&rsquo; <a href=\"/maternity-leave\" title=\"Maternity leave\">maternity leave</a> and to return to their job after this.</p>\n\n<p>What a birth mother does after the child is born has no impact on her right to maternity leave.</p>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice info-notice\">\n<p><a href=\"http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/1985/49\" title=\"‘The Surrogacy Arrangements Act 1985’\" rel=\"external\">Surrogacy laws</a> are very complicated. Find out more about surrogacy on the <a href=\"http://www.hfea.gov.uk/fertility-treatment-options-surrogacy.html\" title=\"Human Fertilisation and Embryology Authority website\" rel=\"external\">Human Fertilisation and Embryology Authority website</a> or talk to a lawyer.</p>\n</div>\n","alternative_title":"Rights for surrogates and surrogate fathers"},"tags":[{"title":"Having a child, parenting and ad